          "body": "The Transjordan defense opens with a triple divine invocation — 'The Mighty One, God, the LORD' repeated twice (22:22) — that is unparalleled in Joshua and rare in the Old Testament. The repetition is not liturgical filler; it is the most solemn oath formula available. They are calling on the all-knowing God to judge whether their inner motive matches their outer act. 'He knows, and may Israel itself know' (22:22) — divine omniscience is cited before human testimony is given, because the crux of the accusation is not the altar's existence but its purpose. The defense is structured as a self-imprecatory oath (22:22-23): if we built this for rebellion or sacrifice, let the LORD require it. Then comes the real reason — spoken in the voices of imagined future descendants: 'your sons may say to our sons, ",
