          "body": "Phinehas's response is one of the most underexamined pastoral moments in Joshua. He hears the explanation — and believes it. 'It pleased them' (22:30). No investigation, no demand for destruction of the altar as a precondition, no further suspicion. The criterion for resolution is the credibility of the spoken word under oath, and Phinehas treats that word as sufficient. His declaration — 'Today we know that the LORD is in our midst, because you have not committed this unfaithful act against the LORD; now you have delivered the sons of Israel from the hand of the LORD' (22:31) — is remarkable for its positive framing. The absence of *maal* is taken as positive evidence of the LORD's presence. Phinehas understands what the western congregation had nearly missed: civil war over innocent brothers would itself have been the act of unfaithfulness that brought divine wrath. The chapter closes with the congregation blessing God (22:33) and the Transjordan tribes naming the altar 'Witness' (22:34): 'it is a witness between us that the LORD is God.' The object that nearly started a war becomes a monument of doxology."
